text:
#taxi #taxis 🚕🚖 💳
ok, as an Italian I feel compelled to give you some advice about taxis in Italy (and expecially in Rome).
- taxis MUST accept credit cards, the system is always working (even if they say it doesn’t) and they can’t ask you to withdraw cash at an ATM. What they are doing is trying to avoid taxes by not declaring all their revenue;
- if you pay cash be sure to always ask a receipt (RICEVUTA o SCONTRINO) at the end: this will help you find the taxi you used if by accident you forget something inside, to report an inappropriate behaviour and you’ll make sure the taxi driver is paying all the taxes he should pay;
- the taximeter MUST always be on, there is no exception;
- taxis are a very strong corporation: in every town there aren’t many taxis because they lobby to prevent the issuance of new licenses (that’s why there are so few Ubers). For italians is even more difficult to catch one than for you as they refuse us because we pay with credit cards, we ask for the taximeter and they can’t rip us too easily. If the price is correct try to take Uber.
EDIT official taxi fares for Rome https://www.comune.roma.it/web-resources/cms/documents/tariffario_taxi_A.pdf
EDIT 2 (sorry admins) SOMETIMES (rarely) credit card system doesn’t actually work, usually in the middle of the countryside: if that is the case probably the driver will be very sorry and will be the first to look for a solution. If it ends that you have to pay with cash ask for a scontrino or ricevuta (invoice).
